We visually compare the two cluster methods, highlighting HDBSCAN's ability to identify noise observations and clusters with irregular shapes, whereas K-Means always assigns every observation to one of the predefined groups.

The two clustering algorithms produce broadly similar results, identifying comparable groups of stocks in the PCA space. However, they differ in how they treat the stocks located in the lower part of the plot. K-Means partitions these observations into two separate clusters, isolating DUK and XOM together while grouping PG, JPM, and ABBV into another cluster. This separation is driven by the algorithm's objective of assigning every observation to one of the predefined clusters. In contrast, HDBSCAN recognises that these stocks belong to the same low-density region and groups them into a single cluster, reflecting their similar risk–return characteristics despite their relatively large distances in the PCA space.

